  "prompt": "What are some good sources for free instrumental music to use in video tutorials?",
  "response": "There are several great sources for free instrumental music that you can use in video tutorials. Here are some of them:\n\n1. **YouTube Audio Library**: YouTube offers a vast collection of free music and sound effects that you can use in your videos. You can filter by genre, mood, instrument, duration, and attribution requirements.\n\n2. **Free Music Archive (FMA)**: FMA provides a wide range of free music across various genres. You can browse by curator or genre to find instrumental tracks suitable for your tutorials.\n\n3. **Incompetech**: Created by Kevin MacLeod, Incompetech offers a large selection of royalty-free music that you can use. The site allows you to search by genre, feel, tempo, and length.\n\n4. **Bensound**: Bensound has a collection of royalty-free music that is free to use with attribution. They offer various genres, including cinematic, acoustic, and electronic.\n\n5. **SoundCloud**: Some artists on SoundCloud offer their music for free under Creative Commons licenses. Make sure to check the licensing terms before using any track.\n\n6. **Jamendo**: Jamendo provides free music for personal use and has licensing options for commercial use. You can explore their extensive library by genre, mood, or theme.\n\n7. **Musopen**: Musopen focuses on classical music and offers recordings, sheet music, and educational resources for free. This is a great source if you need classical instrumental music.\n\n8. **Purple Planet Music**: Purple Planet Music offers royalty-free music that can be used for various projects, including video tutorials. Most of their tracks require attribution.\n\n9. **ccMixter**: ccMixter is a community music site where you can find music under Creative Commons licenses. You can search for instrumental tracks that are free to use with proper attribution.\n\nRemember to always check the licensing terms and give proper attribution if required.",
